<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef493b6d8120a5e624de74b6b273ac25?s=50"></div><header><strong>viewWill/DidAppear and viewWill/DidDisappear should have &quot;animated&quot; argument label (Victor Gao)</strong> from <string>Victor Gao</string> &lt;victorgao44 at gmail.com&gt;<p>June 22, 2016 at 09:00:00am</p></header><div class="content"><p>Hi all,<br></p><p>In the new iOS SDK with Swift 3, I noticed that the viewWillAppear, viewDidAppear, viewWillDisappear and viewDidDisappear hide the animated argument label. Which means when the SDK calls those methods it will look like this:<br></p><p>viewWillAppear(true)<br>viewDidAppear(true)<br>//and others<br></p><p>Obviously this runs counter to the Swift API Design Guidelines, thus results in unclear and confusing code. Instead, these methods should have the â€œanimated&quot; argument label so it would be clear what the boolean flag means.<br></p><p>Cheers,<br>Victor Gao<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
